es of contemporary identity politics. Perceptive and elegantly written, Scenes of Sympathy is the first detailed examination of the place of sympathy in Victorian fiction and ideology. It will redirect the current critical conversation about sympathy and refocus discussions of late-Victorian fictions of identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCapitalism and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGroup identity in literature. 0aLiterature and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aMimesis in literature. 0aSympathy in literature. 4aEurope. 4aFiction & Short Stories. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501719974?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501719974zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501719974/original  a978-3-11-053615-7 Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA